properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, snow and strong winds early next week. An intense low pressure system will affect much of the province Monday afternoon through Wednesday. Rainfall amounts of 20 to 40 millimetres are expected over Southern and Central Quebec. This rain will be accompanied by strong winds with temperatures well above normal. The further east you go, the more rain is expected. The Gaspé Peninsula and the North Shore could receive 50 to 80 millimetres of rain between Tuesday and Wednesday. There too, strong northeast winds combined with poor weather conditions could cause coastal flooding in some areas. Areas further north will receive about 10 centimetres of snow, except for the Manicouagan, which could receive about 20 centimetres of snow. For now, it is still too early to give any specifics for the forecast. Subsequent weather statements will provide more information as the low pressure system's track becomes more certain. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
Expires: 2020-11-29T02:24:51-00:00

properties.Title: Smog Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High concentration of pollutants are expected and will result in poor air quality, especially in urban areas where pollutant emissions are higher. High levels of pollutants are expected to last until Saturday morning. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. In Quebec, wood heating is the main source of fine particles that contribute to smog during winter. This activity generates the largest number of these particulates, more than industrial activities and transportation. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canada’s website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministère de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montréal, visit the Réseau de surveillance de la qualité de l’air de la Ville de Montréal’s website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Québec, visit the Ministère de la Santé et des Services sociaux’s website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction régionale de santé publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-l’Île-de-Montréal at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A strong Pacific frontal system will approach Haida Gwaii today bringing southeast winds of 90 km/h over exposed coastal sections of the North Coast and Haida Gwaii late this afternoon and tonight, The strong winds will ease on Sunday morning. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A frontal system moving across the northern Gulf of Alaska will spread snow at times heavy to Haines road beginning early on Saturday morning. The heaviest snowfall amounts will occur between Pleasant Camp and the Chilkat Pass where 25 cm of snow is expected. Southerly winds of 30 gusting to 50 km/h will accompany the snow reducing visibilities in blowing snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A weather system moving across the central interior continues to bring snow to most of the region. Snow will persist over the McGregor region and Yellowhead Highway past midnight. Additional snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 cm are expected before the snow tapers off overnight. Over the Prince George and Stuart - Nechako regions, snow has eased to a few flurries. Further snowfall amounts will be minimal. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A frontal system moving across the Gulf of Alaska will spread snow at times heavy to the Haines Road and South Klondike Highway beginning this morning. Snowfall amounts up to 25 cm are expected by early Sunday except up to 35 cm between Pleasant Camp and Chilkat Pass. Southerly winds of 40 gusting to 60 km/h will accompany the snow reducing visibilities in blowing snow. Conditions will improve on Sunday as winds ease off with the system moving away. 10 cm of snow are still expected on Sunday near White Pass while 5 cm are forecast for the Haines Road. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Heavy snow and blowing snow is forecast to continue early this morning over Highway 93, with total snowfall accumulations of 20 to 35 cm expected by the time the snow tapers off later this morning. Strong winds are also expected over the region, with local gusts of 60 km/h possible in wind prone areas along the highway. This wind, in combination with the falling snow, will generate low visibility in blowing snow. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 20 to 25 cm is expected. Heavy snow will continue over west-central Alberta tonight, with an additional 10 cm overnight. The snow is expected to taper off on Saturday. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
